Exploration of Alternative Mechanisms To Describe the G-V Shifts In the context of the dual allosteric model, it is possible to generate shifts in G-V curves by changing other parameters that define voltage-dependent gating besides J0, such as L0, zJ, and D, as well as the parameters K and C, which in part define the Ca2+ dependence of gating. We have explored other possible mechanisms in some detail, using different parameter sets in two examples.
Using L26W, which gave the largest G-V shifts, we explored whether changing any one individual parameter could approximate these mutation effects. In Fig. 6 A, we fitted the G-V curves using the wild-type Fit B parameters, and altering only L0. This revealed that decreasing L0 by ‫ف‬100-fold (necessary to generate a +80-mV G-V shift compared with WT at 2.4 μM Ca2+) could not
